# Core Naming Conventions

This guide defines mandatory naming conventions for variables, functions, classes, and general code elements. Consistent naming improves code readability, maintainability, and team collaboration.

## Core Principles

### 1. Use English Language Only

All variables, functions, classes, and files must use English names.

```typescript
// ❌ Bad
const primerNombre = 'John';
const amigos = ['Kate', 'John'];

// ✅ Good
const firstName = 'John';
const friends = ['Kate', 'John'];
```

### 2. Follow camelCase Convention

Use **camelCase** for variables, functions, properties. Use **PascalCase** for classes, interfaces, types.

```typescript
// ❌ Bad
const page_count = 5;
const ShouldUpdate = true;

// ✅ Good
const pageCount = 5;
const shouldUpdate = true;
const userService = new UserService();
```

### 3. S-I-D Rule: Short, Intuitive, Descriptive

Names must be:

- **Short**: Easy to type and remember
- **Intuitive**: Read naturally, close to common speech
- **Descriptive**: Clearly reflect what they do or contain

```typescript
// ❌ Bad
const a = 5; // Too short, not descriptive
const isPaginatable = a > 10; // Unnatural language

// ✅ Good
const postCount = 5;
const hasPagination = postCount > 10;
const shouldPaginate = postCount > 10;
```

## Variable Naming Rules

### Boolean Variables

Use clear prefixes that indicate true/false nature:

```typescript
// ✅ Use 'is' for characteristics or state
const isActive = true;
const isLoading = false;
const isValid = user.email.includes('@');

// ✅ Use 'has' for possession
const hasPermission = user.roles.includes('ADMIN');
const hasErrors = validationErrors.length > 0;

// ✅ Use 'should' for conditional actions
const shouldUpdate = currentVersion !== latestVersion;
const shouldShowModal = !user.hasSeenWelcome;

// ✅ Use 'can' for capabilities
const canDelete = user.role === 'ADMIN';
const canEdit = user.id === post.authorId;
```

### Collections and Counts

Use singular/plural appropriately:

```typescript
// ❌ Bad
const friends = 'Bob'; // Should be singular
const friend = ['Bob', 'Tony']; // Should be plural

// ✅ Good
const friend = 'Bob';
const friends = ['Bob', 'Tony'];
const userCount = 42;
const activeUsers = users.filter((u) => u.isActive);
```

### Boundaries and Limits

Use `min/max` prefixes for boundaries:

```typescript
// ✅ Good
const minPasswordLength = 8;
const maxRetryAttempts = 3;
const minPrice = 0;
const maxFileSize = 10 * 1024 * 1024; // 10MB
```

## Function Naming Rules

### A/HC/LC Pattern

Follow the pattern: `prefix? + action + highContext + lowContext?`

| Function Name          | Prefix | Action  | High Context | Low Context |
| ---------------------- | ------ | ------- | ------------ | ----------- |
| `getUser`              | -      | get     | User         | -           |
| `getUserMessages`      | -      | get     | User         | Messages    |
| `shouldDisplayMessage` | should | Display | Message      | -           |
| `isPaymentEnabled`     | is     | -       | Payment      | Enabled     |

### Standard Action Verbs

#### `get` - Access immediate data

```typescript
getUserFullName(): string {
  return `${this.firstName} ${this.lastName}`;
}
```

#### `fetch` - Retrieve data asynchronously

```typescript
async fetchUserById(id: string): Promise<User> {
  return this.userRepository.findOne({ where: { id } });
}
```

#### `set` - Assign values declaratively

```typescript
setUserStatus(userId: string, status: UserStatus): void {
  this.userStatusMap.set(userId, status);
}
```

#### `reset` - Return to initial state

```typescript
resetPassword(userId: string): void {
  this.setUserPassword(userId, this.generateTempPassword());
}
```

#### `create` - Generate new entities

```typescript
async createUser(userData: CreateUserDto): Promise<User> {
  return this.userRepository.save(userData);
}
```

#### `remove` - Take away from collection

```typescript
removeUserFromRole(userId: string, roleId: string): void {
  this.userRoles.delete(`${userId}-${roleId}`);
}
```

#### `delete` - Permanently destroy

```typescript
async deleteUser(id: string): Promise<void> {
  await this.userRepository.delete(id);
}
```

#### `update` - Modify existing data

```typescript
async updateUser(id: string, updates: UpdateUserDto): Promise<User> {
  return this.userRepository.update(id, updates);
}
```

#### `validate` - Check correctness

```typescript
validateEmail(email: string): boolean {
  return /^[^\s@]+@[^\s@]+\.[^\s@]+$/.test(email);
}
```

## Class and File Naming

### NestJS Components

Follow NestJS conventions with descriptive suffixes:

```typescript
// Controllers
export class UserController {} // user.controller.ts
export class AuthController {} // auth.controller.ts

// Services
export class UserService {} // user.service.ts
export class EmailService {} // email.service.ts

// DTOs
export class CreateUserDto {} // user.dto.ts
export class UpdateUserDto {} // user.dto.ts
export class UserResponseDto {} // user.dto.ts

// Guards
export class JwtAuthGuard {} // jwt-auth.guard.ts
export class PermissionGuard {} // permission.guard.ts

// Commands & Queries (CQRS)
export class CreateUserCommand {} // create-user.command.ts
export class GetUserByEmailQuery {} // get-user-by-email.query.ts
```

### Avoid Context Duplication

Don't repeat the class context in method names:

```typescript
// ❌ Bad - duplicates context
class UserService {
  getUserById(id: string) {} // "User" is already in class name
  createNewUser(data: any) {} // "User" is redundant
}

// ✅ Good - clean method names
class UserService {
  findById(id: string) {}
  create(data: CreateUserDto) {}
  update(id: string, data: UpdateUserDto) {}
  delete(id: string) {}
}
```

## Constants and Enums

### Constants

Use SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE for constants:

```typescript
// ✅ Good
const MAX_RETRY_ATTEMPTS = 3;
const DEFAULT_PAGE_SIZE = 20;
const JWT_EXPIRY_TIME = '24h';
const BCRYPT_SALT_ROUNDS = 10;
```

### Enums

Use PascalCase for enum names and SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE for values:

```typescript
// ✅ Good
enum UserStatus {
  ACTIVE = 'ACTIVE',
  INACTIVE = 'INACTIVE',
  SUSPENDED = 'SUSPENDED',
  PENDING_VERIFICATION = 'PENDING_VERIFICATION',
}

enum HttpStatusCode {
  OK = 200,
  CREATED = 201,
  BAD_REQUEST = 400,
  UNAUTHORIZED = 401,
  NOT_FOUND = 404,
}
```

## Common Mistakes to Avoid

### Don't Use Contractions

```typescript
// ❌ Bad: getUsrNme(), calcTtl()
// ✅ Good: getUserName(), calculateTotal()
```

### Don't Use Abbreviations

```typescript
// ❌ Bad: usr, cfg, btn
// ✅ Good: user, config, button
```

### Reflect Expected Results

```typescript
// ❌ Bad - confusing logic
const isEnabled = itemCount <= 3;
if (!isEnabled) {
  /* awkward */
}

// ✅ Good - clear intent
const isDisabled = itemCount <= 3;
if (isDisabled) {
  /* natural */
}
```

Following these core naming conventions ensures your code is readable, maintainable, and follows industry best practices.
